{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/0027955839A/1938010701/0040.xml":{"full_text":"When Wedding Came to Bedridden Bridesmaid\nbell, the bride, and Rev. Howard Spunglcr.\nFRANK TAKES\nPOST IN G.O.P.\nI\nNew Program Committee\nChairman Explains\nDelay in Action\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 7. (IT)\nDr. Glenn Frank, former presi\ndent of the University of Wiscon\nsin, last night accepti-'d the chair\nmanship of the newly formed pro\ngram committee oi' the Republi\ncan party and appealed for non\nparti^'in co-operation to relieve\nthe \"gravity of a situation which\ncuts across all sections and all\njf roups.\"\nFrank's message of acceptance,\nmade public by Chairman John D.\nM. Hamilton of the Republican\nnational committee, sai<! he was\naccepting the new post without\n\"any prior obligation\" since no\none had communicated with him j\nat the time the committee was\nformed recently in St. Louis, Mo.\nHe acknowledged that the \"bus-\niness\" of the program group is\nnot to promote the interests of I\nany candidate nor is it to write\nplatforms which he said is a task\nfor state and national party con\nventions.\n\"Since office-holders of the\nparty are not in its membership.\" 1\nFrank's telegram said, \"this com- j\nmission is a body of laymen ;isk-.\ned to devote themselves behind j\nthe lines of formal party action j\nto a study of the extraordinarily\ngrave social and economic diffi\nculties that now confront the na- j\ntion.\n\"The Republican party recog-1\nniZes its obligations in the pres\nent critical situation to call out\nand mobilize the full resources of\nintelligence and action that the\nrank ant! file of its millions of\nadherents possess.\n\"The gravity of the situation\ncuts across the traditional boun\ndaries of all parties, all sections\nand all groups. I hope, therefore,1\nthat this commission will have\naccess to the deepest desires and\nbest thoughts of workers, farm\ners, professional men and wo\nmen, business men, small and\nlarge, regardless of party lines o.\nsectional interests.\n\"As 1 sense the spirit of the\nmembers who have already w' it\nt\u00abn to me this commission will\nnyt be an agency of petty fault\nrinding or vindictive attack. It\nwill seek to play its full part in\na sincere, open-minded responsi\nble search for the principles ami,\nlines of national action that will j\nkeep America a going concern\u2014\nwith its business .its industry and\nits agriculture administering et-j\nfeitiveJy to the human needs ol\nthe whole people and insure a\nway of UfQ congenial to the I\nAmerican spirit.\"\nFrank explained he had delay\ned in accepting the nomination\nbecause at the time lie was ncti\nfnid of the committee's action he\nwas not in a position to assume\na \"major obligation of this sort\nuntil .1 had made the necessary\nreadjustments in my other obliga\ntions. That alone accounts for\ntbis delayed acceptance.\"\nFREDERIKA LUISE\nIS IN ATHENS FOR\nWEDDING SUNDAY\nATHENS, .Jan. 7. (UP)\u2014More j\nthan 200.000 persons many <>i 1\nwhom had waited six hours in bit\ninK cold weather cheered the ar\nMval in Athens last night of Prin\nFrederika LuiSe. granddaugh\nter of Kx-Kaiser VV'ilhelm II, and\nCrown Prince Paul of Greece, who\nwill be married Sunday.\nThe special train bringim* the\nprincess and her parents from\nAustria was six hours late, held\nup by heavy snows and storms in\ncputoil Europe that also delayed\nthe arrival of several royal guests\ncoming for one of the most hril\nItanl weddings in years.\nThe \"5-year-old Prince Paul,\nbrother of King George 11 and\nheir presumptive to the Greek\nthrone, went to the Yugoslav fron\ntier to meet his fiancee.\nThe train carrying the 20-year\ndld princess who may some day\nrule over nearly 8,000.000 Greeks\nwas brilliantly illuminated when it\nleft Saloni^fr pt i> a. m. Each\nqoach was at^i-Meuuted by a huge\ncrown in ^dfri^lisrhts of many\ncolors.\nIS DUE CHAIR,\nKILLER SAYS\nConvict Confessing to Wo\nman's Murder Not Fear\ning Consequences\nLOnsVlM.K. Ky.. .I:\u00abn. 7.\u2014\nH'P> \u2014A 1 D-year-old ex-convict\nw!io confessed the slaying of Mrs.\nYYilma Carpenter In her Philadei-!\nphia suburb homo last December\nL'{, said last night that \"I'm not\nafraid of the electric chair, it's\ncoming to me.\"\n\"I've been stealing and robbing\nsince I've been knee high to a\ngrasshopper,\" ti>e youth, Wendell\nForrest Howers, said. \"My moth\ner died when I was 11 months old\nand I've never had a home since.\nI've been tossed around so much\n1 had to turn to stealing to ex\nist.\"\nBowers was held by Louisville\npolice for two weeks on a vagran\ncy charge and was about to be re\nleased when G-men discovered\nduring a routine fingerprint check\nthat his prints were those of Mrs.\nCarpenter's killer.\nHe pleaded guilty before L:. S.\nCommissioner Kay II. Kirchbor\nster to unlawful flight to avoid\nprosecution and was returned to\nthe Jefferson county jail under\n$25,000 bond. The youth confess\ned the crime when confronted j\nwith the fingerprint evidence.\nJohn K. Flynn, assistant district\nattorney of .Montgomery county.\nPennsylvania, who arrived last i\nnight by plane, will probably re\nturn the prisoner to .Norristown,\nPa., near Philadelphia, to face\nmurder charges today. Bovvers\nfirst will be arraigned on two mi\nnor charges in Louisville in the\nmorning.\nChief of Police John Malley\nsaid Bowers, in his confession de\nscribed in iletail how he attempt\ned to attack Mary Grifi'in, 22,\nMrs. Carpenter's companion and\nbusiness associate, when they re\nturned and found him ransacking\nthe Carpenter home.\nBowers, according to Malley, I\nsaid he struck Mis:? Griffin on the\nhead, forced her to disrobe part\nly. She beat him off, however, i\nand after taking u bath he thumb- i\ned a ride to a railroad station.\nCHARGES MADE\nIN NEW JERSEY\nWAR ON C.I.O.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 7. (UP).\u2014\nCharges of tampering with Uni\nted States mails and threat of u\nfederal investigation last night\nwere tossed into the feud be\ntween Mayor Frank Hague of Jer\nsey City, N. .1.. and the Commit\ntee for Industrial Organization,\nwhich the New Jersey mayor has j\ndriven out of his city.\nErnst exhibited copies of a pho-\ntostate of a letter, written on\nAmerican Civil Liberties Union\nletterhead, which appeared in sev\neral morning newspapers on Jan.\n\u2022I. purporting to be copies of a I\nletter written to several persons j\nin New Jersey and signed by Kog\ner N. Baldwin, director of tin\nunion.\nHe said the letter was sent in\nduplicate to several persons in\nNew Jersey \"but the original was\nthe only one on Civil Liberties\nUnion stationery.\"\nHe said that it was sent to Syd\nRose, chairman of the Hudson\ncounty committee of the C. I.\nIt was misdirected, according to\nErnst, and \"by a lucky break\" it\nwas returned to the Civil Liber\nties Union offices Jan. 3, still\nsealed and apparently unopened.\nThe next day, Ernst said, the\nphotostat of the letter sent to\nRose appeared in the newspapers,\nwhich he charged obtained them\nin a press handout\" released\nthrough Mayor Hague's offices.\nHe said he would formally\ncharge that \"someone acting in\nthe interest of Mayor Hague'' has\ninterfered with the mails.\nA second charge which Ernst\nsaiti he would place before Cum\nmings concerned a letter asserted\nly written to Robert A mby of Jer\nsey City, political .opponent of\nMayor Hague, .which. vwa>> mailed\nDee. 15 and-which has not been\nI received.\nH.H.S, QUINT TO\nOPEN SEASON\nGame With Tryon Will Be\nat City Gym Here\nTonight\nAttention was called today l<>\nthe fact that the lUndersonville\nTryon basketball game which had\nbeen scheduled for Tryon tonight\nwill be played here this evening\ninstead.\nInterest in city basketball ha.4\nluuKc'd f\u00ab\u00bbr the past i.wo years, but\nin view of the fart that a com\nfortable gym is now available and\nHendersonville high school has two\ngood teams, it is anticipated that\nthe sport will be more widely fol\nlowed this year than recently.\nAnother item which will build\nup interest is the forthcoming\nHlue Ridge tournament.\nPublic support for the game to\nnight is invited by the team spon\nsors. A small admission will be\ncharged.\npork\"barreT FIGHT\nGOES TO HOUSE FLOOR\n(Continued from one*\nbitterly assailed a $123,669,000\nslash in funds foe the Civilian Con\nservation Corps which was recom\nmended by Mr. Roosevelt.\n'*1 warn you this i-- the begin\nning of the end of the Civilian\nConservation Corps,\" he shouted.\n\"The CCC has been Merreted out'\nfor slashing. Don't abandon these\ncamps in the name of economy,\nbecause next week a message will\ncome here calling for 20 new $00,\n000.000 battleships.\"\nThe house appropriations com\nmittee took into account President\nRoosevelt's suggestions for econ\nomy in \"pork barrel\" outlays by\nreporting the bill, which carries\nfunds for .'{7 independent federal\nagencies, with a slash of $3,732,\n02(1 below budget estimates and\n$118,538,000 under the current\nyear's funds.\nJohnson's attack coincided with\nanother slap at economy by Chair\nman Wilburn Cartwright, Dem.,\nOkla.. of the house roads commit\ntee, who introduced a bill propos\ning to continue through 1940 and\n1941 a $400,000,00(1 federal high\nway aid program that Mr. Roose\nvelt wants repealed.\nThe budget estimates call for a\n$140,000,000 cut in this depart\nment during the 1939 fiscal year\nand for elimination thereafter.\n\"I am a strong advocate of econ\nomy but believe reductions should\nbe mude in all agencies of the gov\nernment and not just make roads\nthe 'goat',\" Cartwright said.\nThis led to more denunciations\nof the president's program.\n\"The man in the White House\nhas never known and never will\nknow how a dollar is made,\" Rep.\nJames W. Wadsworth, R., N. Y.,\ncontended. \"The nation will have\nt<> dedicate itself to fchrift, com\nmmi sense and frugality to get out\nof its present financial condition.\"\nRep. Arthur P. Lamneck, I\nasserted that he \"no longer\ncan j;o along\" with the adminis\ntration because the solution of the\nbudget and economic problems\nrests with congress. 4\nIn the senate, administration\n1 -aders had a tough job control\n1 ng a filibuster by 15 southern\nsenators who are being aided by\nSen. William 10. Borah, R., Ida.,\nn their fight against the lynch\nbill.\nThe discussion, which began\nwith a burst of vituperation, de\ngenerated into a serio-comic exhi\nbition when, during a dull mo\nment. youthful Sen- Henry Cabot\nLodge, R.. Mass., whA was presid\nine-, sprawled on the rostrum when\nhis chair upset.\nJAPANESE BEAT 2\nBRITISH POLICEMEN\n(Continued from rage one)\nyards will be diverted to the Ital\nians \"to he employed in the west\nern Mediterranean and Indian\nocean.\"\nThe documents said the trans\nport ships from Japan were tc\nhave been delivered to Russia un\nder liquidation of an arrangement\nfor transfer of control of the Chi\nnese. Eastern railway to Japan.\nItaly, it*w;t* stated, will not pay\nJapan for the ships until the eco\nnomic situation improves.\nWarsaw Reports\n'Mrs. Robinson'\nSlain In Russia\nLONDON. Jan. 7. (UP)\u2014'The\nDaily Mlriw's correspondent at\nWarsaw reported todav that Mrs.\nDonald L. kobinson, identified yes\nterday as Ruth Maine Rubens of\n.Ww York, has been executed by\na Russian firing squad in a Mos\ncow orison.\n(The repoi't could not be veri\nfied in Moscow emly today. Fre\nquentlv there are baseless reports\nemanating- from Warsaw regard\ning affairs in Russia.)\nThe Daily Minor's Warsaw dis\npatch made no mention of the f\u00bbti\nof the man known .ns \"Donald L.\nRobinson.\" supposedly Mrs. flu\nhens' husband. Adolpn Arnold Ru\nbens.\nThe disnalch said the woman\nwas executed by an O.upu (Rus\nsian secret nolirc.) firing squad al\nter being identified a.; the wife of\nRussian colonel. Armanow, who\nd'\"d in a Soviet concentration\ncamp.\nTtio mysterious \"Mr. Robinson''\nwho disanpeared from the Xi't'on\nal hotel in Moscow a few days\nlore Ihr disappearance of \"Mrs.\nRobinson\" on Dec. was said bv\nthe Daily Mirror to have been\nidentified as Russian engineer\nnamed Rokolikoff, who escaped\nfrom a Soviet prison and became\na United States citizen.\nThe dispatch described \"Mrs.\nRobinson\" as a former Russian\nactress who fled to the United\nStates and returned to Russia un\nder the name Robinson in an ef\nfort to locate her husband. She\nused a \u2022falsfl\" American passport.\nMAN QUERIED DENIES\nPASSPORTS FRAUD\n(Continued \u2666\u2022\u2022\u2022'.\u2022n; one)\nHe was believed to have been the\n\"key man\" in a curious chain of\npersonalities through which the\nRobinsons supposedly obtained the\npassports.\nSharfin, also known as Aaron\nSharfin, tiirncri up in tin* case af\nter another alphabetical witness,\na \"Mr. subsequently identified\nas Harry Zuckerman. named him\nas the final link in the passport\nchain.\nZuckerman told authorities he\nhad received a request from \"Mr.\nD\"\u2014whom he then named as\nLouis Kpstein\"\u2014to obtain a pass\nport through a chain of \"con\ntracts,\" which he explained was\nthe political cuphism for \"favors.\"\nThe contracts ultimately reached\nthe office of former County Clerk\nAlbert Marinelli, target of District\nAttorney Thomas F Dewey's cam\npaign charges which ultimately\nforced Marinelli's resignation.\nThere the application was drafted\nwithout the formality of personal\nappearance.\nAfter Zuekevman walked out of\nthe room where state department\nmen were questioning witnesses,\nhe exclaimed:\n\"I feel like a now man\u2014I'm\nglad that's over, and I'm sorry I\nspent so much time protecting a\nman who didn't deserve it.\"\nSharfin was then brought to\nthe federal building, and for sev\neral hours contributed to the ex\ncitement of attending newspaper\nreporters by scuttling in and out\nof elevators, ducking behind pil\nlars and covering his face with\nhis bat when news photographers\ntried to shoot pictures.\nHowever, federal agents failed\nto indicate whether he had con\ntributed materially to the absorb\ning mystery of why the \"Robin\nsons\" vanished nito a Soviet pris\non last month after entering thi>\ncountry on fake passports. He re\nmained under subpena for further\nquestioning.\nDispatches from Moscow iden\ntified. Mrs. Robinson as Mrs.\nAdolph Arbold Rubens, an Ameri\ncan citizen, but Sharfin said he\ndid not know either Mrs. Rubens\nor Robinson, and had nothing to\ndo with their passports.\nHe was first described b.v agents\nas \"secretary\" to the Egyptian\nconsul, but the consulate later said\nhe was merely houseboy who\nworked at the consulate offices at\n10.1 Park avenue.\nNEW DEAL-BUSINESS\nDEBATE IS STAGED\nNEW TORK. Ian. 7 \u2014(UP)\u2014\nSpokasmwufor the New Deal and\nbijr business clashed in debate last\nnight, each demanding that the\nothers act to lift the nation out of\nthe business recession.\nWhile 1,700 persons cheered\nand booed in Town Hall. Assistant\nAttorney General Robert H. Jack\nson, mentioned as a presidential\ncandidate for 1910, called on big\nbusiness to speed up production,\nlower prices a'\"d maintain the\nhighest possible wages.\nOutside in West 4.'Jd street 500\npersons pushed at the doors, de\nmanding admittance, as Wendell\nL. Willkie, president of the Com\nmonwealth and Southern Corpora\ntion. one of the nation's great\nUtility holding companies, demand\ned that the government restore\nconfidence so small investors would\nput up the money that industry\nneeds to finance improvements'and\nprovide jobs.\nBAPTIST S. S. GROUP\nMEET SET SUNDAY\nA Haptist Associations! Sunday\nschool group meeting will bo -held\nat 3 p. m. Sunday at Calvary\nchurch. Miss\" Izora Reece, super\nintendent of group No. 0, will be\niu charge of the program. This\ngroup is composed of the fallow\ning churches: Uendersonville\nFirst, Valley Hill, Shaws Creek,\nBalfour, West Hendersonville,\nRefuge, Ebenczer, East Flat Rock\nand Calvary. .An investing pro\ngram is. being arraif**d and the\npublic is invited.\n2 EXONORATED\nIN KILLING OF\nJACK MORGAN\nMen Who Delivered Body\nto Sharks Not Questioned\nby Grand Jury\nLOS ANGELES, Jan. 7. (I'D\nThe federal grand jury late yes\nterday exonerated Robert Home\nand George Sneinacit, the young\ndeckhands who threw overboard\nsm amateur pirate after he had\nkilied the skipper of the schooner\nyacht A A I'M K and for four days\nruled the boat with mailed list.\nThe grand jury, in returning a\n\"no hill,\" derided the two deck\nhands acted in self-defence in\nthiowing .Jack Morgan to t.ie\nsharks after he fatally shoi Dwight\nFaulding, owner of tlie AAl-JK.\nand terrorized crew and prsjen\njreir while setting a course for the\nSouth Pacific.\nImmediately after the report\nwus nuulr to Ffderal Hsuij\nA. ilollzer, a deputy V. S. mar\nshal was sent to the county jail\nv, ith an order to release the young\nprisoners, who had heen held on a\nmurder complaint.\nA second order was issued, pro\nviding for the release of Mrs. fi\nlial! Morgan. 17-year-old common\nlaw wife of Morgan, who killed co\npursue the career of a pirate.\nThe girl, an expectant mother,\nhad heen held as a material w.t-j\nness since the AAF.IK was towed\ninto San Pedro last week hy a\ncoast .guard cutter which found I\nher floundering in h avy seas off\nthe coast of lower California.\nThe jury had questioned only\nthree witnesses, Mrs. Morgan, M\nsie Herdan. 22-year-old nurse, and\nMrs. (Jertrude Turner. Faulding's\nfiancee, all of whom were passen\ngers aboard the yacht duiing the\neight-day cruise from San Pedro.\nThe women repeated substan\ntially the same stories they had\ntold federal bureau of investiga\ntion agents\u2014that Morgan shot:\nFaulding in cold blood three\nhours al ter the A A I'M K sailed,\nseized control of the boat, and i\ndominated the passengers and\ncrew at the point of a gun.\nHis mastery ended four days\nlater when Home, enraged by the j\nabuse he had endured, seized a j\nmarl in spike, hit Morgan on the,\nhead and with the help of Sper\nnack threw him into shark-infect-1\ned waters off the coast of Mexico, j\nSpernack and Home were anx-1\nious to give their versions to, the I\ngrand jury, but they were j not\ncalled.\nCHARLESTONIANS\nWILL HONOR FIRST\nU. S. WEATHERMAN\nCHARLESTON', S. C... Jan. 7.\n(UP)\u2014The pioneer efforts oj\" Dr.\nJohn Lining. America's first\nweatherman, will be commemo\nrated by an unveilihg service I.ere\nthe week of January 9 '200 j\nyears after the first weather study\nwas made.\nW. R. Gregjj, chief of the U. S.\nWeather bureau, Washington, will\nattend the unveiling of u tablet\non the building in which Dr. Lin\ning lived\u2014anil worked. The build\ning is believed to have been the\nfirst drug store in this country,\nas well as the first weather ob\nservatory.\nDr. Lining's observations were\nmade with instruments similar in\nprinciple to those used today.\nBUMPER SAVES CHILD\nCLEVELAND. (UP).\u2014An au\ntomobile bumper served as a saf\nety \"catcher\" for 7-year-old Rita\nKalhoun. When a car struck her,\nphe bounced to a seating position\non the bumper and rode along,\nsafe from injury.\nAs Millions Apply for Unemployment Benefits\nWaiting patiently in a long shuffling line, these St. Paul, Minn., workmen are seeking to i<: vr\nfor unemployment insurance benefits, payment of which is getting \"under way in 21 states and\nDistrict of Columbia. Payment ol $300,000,000 in these benefits is a line of seif-det'ense against\ning employment which is expected to helD curb the business recession.\nGIRL, Zi QUALIFIES AS\nCAPTAIN OF TUGBOAT\nPORT .M.RHii.VI, II. .Inn.I\n7. (L'P)\u2014Dorothy Oiurice l!hick\nniore, a 2.'J-y\u00ab>ar-old blonde. i\nplanning to he Canada's first wo\nman tugboat captain.\nDorothy recently passed her x\namination for a tugboat master's\ncertificate under supervising \u00ab-x-;\naminer Lionel If. J,inds:iv of V.mi-;\neouver, and confirmation from\nOttawa is expected soon.\nThe tfirl has spent, six years <>n f\nher father's tu\u00bbboat and is a hiuh\nschool graduate.\nZIRCONIA\nZIRCONIA, Jan. 7.\u2014 Members j\nof Green River Maptist church\ngave Ifev. S. Huntley, pastor,\na nice poundip.f>* for Christmas.\nMr. and Mrs. L*. S. Staton re\ncently visited the latter'* parents.\nMr. and Mrs. J. T. Jones of Jones i\nGap.\nMr. and Mrs. I.. K. Pace and\nfamily and Mr. mid Mrs. W. I''\nI'ace visited Mr. and Mrs. Allen\nCorn of Flat Kock, January '1.\nThe young folks of tlx- com\nmunity enoyed ;i new year's party\nand stake fry at the home of\nClyde Morgan. Ahont IS boys\nand girls were present. The Levi\nbrothers furnished string music.\nJ. L. Pace, who has been ill\nfor some time, is not improving I\nvery fast.\nMiss Lois Pace and John Pace!\nwere over-night guests of Mary!\nand Arthur Staton, December Ml.!\nD. K. Staton of Mt. Holly,\nspent the Christmas holidays with\nhis family.\nMrs. Joe Ward and son, Clyde,\nhave moved back to their farm in\nthe Double Springs section. Peo\nple are glad to welcome them.\nMrs. W. C. I.evi and Misses\nLeta and Essie Levi visited at\nthe home of Mrs. (J. C. Andrews\nSu nday.\nMrs. Tom Jones visited Mrs. J.\nL. L. Pace Monday.\nMrs. J. |J. Queen visited Mrs.\nW. I.. Staton last Sunday.\n\"MEANEST MAN\" ROBS UP\nPA J A110. Cal. (UP) This\ncity's candidate for the \"meanest\nman\" entered the aviary of M\"s.\nW. II. West and wrung the i.ecks j\nof five canaries.\nTHOROUGHBRED\nHORSE SECURED\nFOR BREEDING\nThrough the cooperation of the\nfederal government and tiie Unit\n\u00ab*i I States cavalry, Henderson\ncounty and the surrounding t.'i\nlilory lias received a thorough\nlued stud horse for breeding pur\nposes.\nThe horse was brought here\nfro in the Cavalry Remount Sta\ntic. ii at Lexington, Ky., and has i\nbeen placed at Camp Mondamit*.\nTuxedo.\nA cross with the present stock\nin the county and this horse will\nproduce the typical cavalry hoise\nand a line breed for general\nw\u00ab\u00bbrk. ('rossing with hunters and\njumpers also produces a good\nbreed.\nStud fees will be announced at\n;i later date and breeding will be-\njiin February 15.\nHENDERS0NV1LLE\nSCHOOLS HAVE OWN\nCHAPTER IN F. F. A.,\nThe boys of the new depart\nment of vocational agriculture in\nthe Hend\u00ab'\u00bb\\sonvil)e city schools\nhave recently organized a chapter\nof Future Farmers. The F.F.A.\nis a national organization com\nposed only by boys studying vo\ncational agriculture. There are\n12,000 such students in the Uni\nted States in <>000 high school,\nstudying agriculture. It has been 1\nsaid that if we had been teaching\nagriculture to the farm youth for\nthe last 50 years we would not\ntoday have HO,000,000 acres of\nland worn out and unfit for\nprofitable farming:.\nOne hundred percent of the ag\nriculture boys in the Heiiderson\nville school are members of the\nF.F.A. club. The officers are as\nfollows: J. C. Coston, Jr., presi\ndent; Ross Douglass, vice-presi\ndent; Aubrey Horn, secretary;\nSeldon Shipnian, treasurer; Mar\nion Horn, reporter; J. F. Corbin,\nadvisor.\nFor convenience in having meet\ning- and attending to business\neach class has a set of officers\nand a program is carried out\ntwice each month. We have or\nganized a thrift club in connec\ntion with our chapter.\nThe treasurer is the cashier,\nand the brink i always\nreceive deposits. i lie 11\u2022\ntin it-, fhc money over to ii\nvi .Mr. Oorbin, who i.~ n.\ni! for ai'tl banks it.\nSity peicent of the inci\nhave money on deposit and\nof it has been drawn out n\ntlii< was started K<) days a^;\nWe also pay 10 cents :rr\nmonth dues, pa't of which ,i>\nour state dues.\nThe organization has lout <ir\n;'iies of membership based\nachievement: (ireenhand, Fu; tr\na i m e r. State Farmer i.\n\\iin riean farmer.\nTl;.. (wo I'ii l decrees are w\nIdled in the local chapter. j\nthird at Ii;\u00bbleiyli sit tlu* sinna: |1\nstate meeting held each July, ar 3\ntiie fourth is conferred in Kansi |1\nf'ity, Mo., at the annual mcctii J\nheld in October.\u2014Marion I\nreporter.\nFRENCH LIGHTHOUSE\nWILL BE LARGEST\nIN ENTIRE WORLI\nPARIS. Jan. 7. (UP)\u2014A nn\nlighthouse, declared f be the ni\"<\npowerful iu the world, will\nerected within the next year\ntin- island <if Ouessant in th\u00ab' At\nlantie ocean about 25 miles v.\u00ab\nof IJrest. It will take the pla<<*o!\nth\u00ab* lighthouse at Croac'h uhid\nserved as a guide to Anuiitai\ntroon ships on their way to Kianc\u00bb\nin I0I7-1S.\nShips 50 iniles distant w ll ix\nable to see the beams of tin- mt\nlighthouse and its lights will havr\na total strength of .jOO,OOfl,00(\ncandlepower. Each ten \u00abeeont\ntwo moving: beams will vivWft\neach lasting two-tenths <>t .1\nond.\nA masterpiece of I'rt ix\nscience, the lighthous.- will >n.-:<\nof a tower 05 feet hih >um; li\ned by a giant lantern, tin n-voiv\ninjr lamps of which will\nin height.\nThe island on which th<- lijrfct\nhouse will be built i< k 1.\u2022 r. a\n\"the end of the world\" :\u00bbnd\nfavorite visiting place foi tniir;*\nin Brittanv. It has .1 i\nof .'?,000.\nCapetown, South Afric\nbutter shortage and supp.:\nbeing shipped several\nmiles from Great Rritaii\nA Young Hendersonville\nBusiness Man\nI am a little merchant, typical of all carriers of The Times\nNews. I buy and sell papers just as any other retail mer\nchant buys and sells his product. I am an independent mer\nchant and my profit is the difference between my collections\nfrom my customers and the wholesale price I pay The Times\nNews for my papers.\nI am learning business practices that will enable me to cope\nwith real and bigger situations in later life. If I fail to collect\nfrom a customer I not only lose my profit, but also the whole\nsale price of the paper. I am learning to deal with the public\nand while learning I am paying my way, earning money for\nmy school clothes and expenses and building up a nice savings\naccount. I will appreciate your cooperation.\nThank You.\nYOUR TIMES-NEWS CARRIER\nh\". \"t/!* 1","height":"27813","width":"20268"}}
